abstract: After years of looking for genetic mutations that cause diseases, investigators are now searching for those that prevent them.
snippet: After years of looking for genetic mutations that cause diseases, investigators are now searching for those that prevent them.
lead_paragraph: Doug Whitney should have died years ago. The 65-year-old resident of Port Orchard, Wash., has a devastating gene mutation that — according to the medical literature — causes early onset Alzheimer’s disease in everyone who inherits it.

abstract: Alzheimer’s is deadly, costly and finally getting the blunt discussion it needs.

lead_paragraph: My maternal grandmother lives in my memory as two distinct images. Two distinct people, really.

abstract: New York’s attorney general had accusing Actavis of forcing patients to switch to a newer version of the drug to thwart competition from generic manufacturers.
snippet: New York’s attorney general had accusing Actavis of forcing patients to switch to a newer version of the drug to thwart competition from generic manufacturers.
lead_paragraph: A federal judge has decided to block for now an attempt by the drug company Actavis to halt sales of an older form of its Alzheimer’s disease drug Namenda in favor of a newer version with a longer patent life.

abstract: The writing-directing married pair behind “Still Alice,” about a woman struck by Alzheimer’s, are dealing with a different disease, A.L.S.
snippet: The writing-directing married pair behind “Still Alice,” about a woman struck by Alzheimer’s, are dealing with a different disease, A.L.S.
lead_paragraph: LOS ANGELES — One of this year’s surprise cinematic success stories centers on the independent film “Still Alice,” which tells the tale of an Ivy League linguistics professor dealing with early-onset Alzheimer’s.

abstract: When it’s used inaccurately to fight problems like poverty, some critics fear neuroscience could hurt more than it helps.
snippet: When it’s used inaccurately to fight problems like poverty, some critics fear neuroscience could hurt more than it helps.
lead_paragraph: The idea that poverty can change the brain has gotten significant attention recently, and not just from those lay readers (a minority, according to recent research) who spend a lot of time thinking about neuroscience. Policy makers and others have begun to apply neuroscientific principles to their thinking about poverty — and some say this could end up harming poor people rather than helping.

abstract: Whittier, who in 1969 became the first black player on the Texas football team, has filed a proposed federal class-action lawsuit, saying that the N.C.A.A. failed to warn players of the risks that head trauma presented.
snippet: Whittier, who in 1969 became the first black player on the Texas football team, has filed a proposed federal class-action lawsuit, saying that the N.C.A.A. failed to warn players of the risks that head trauma presented.
lead_paragraph: Julius Whittier, who in 1969 became the first black player on the Texas football team, has filed a proposed federal class-action lawsuit, saying that the N.C.A.A. failed to warn players of the risks that head trauma presented. The suit seeks relief for all N.C.A.A. football players from 1960 to 2014 who did not play in the N.F.L. and have been found to have “a latent brain injury or disease.”

abstract: The documentary, directed by James Keach, follows Glen Campbell’s final tour, as he and his family deal with his decline from Alzheimer’s disease.
snippet: The documentary, directed by James Keach, follows Glen Campbell’s final tour, as he and his family deal with his decline from Alzheimer’s disease.
lead_paragraph: From the very first scene, “I’ll Be Me” signals that it is not going to be a conventional documentary about a celebrity, in this case the country-pop singer and guitarist Glen Campbell. As Mr. Campbell sits in a darkened room watching home movies of his younger self, he asks his wife, Kim, “Who is that?”

headline.print_headline: A Farewell to His Fans and Himself

abstract: “Glen Campbell ... I’ll Be Me,” a documentary by James Keach, captures the final concert tour of a country music legend in the grip of Alzheimer’s disease.
snippet: “Glen Campbell ... I’ll Be Me,” a documentary by James Keach, captures the final concert tour of a country music legend in the grip of Alzheimer’s disease.
lead_paragraph: The scenes of politicians urging financing for Alzheimer’s research really aren’t necessary. The sight of Glen Campbell struggling as a teleprompter feeds him the lyrics to songs everyone in his audience knows by heart is all that is needed to put across what’s at stake.

abstract: “Brain training” games have become big business, but the research is still unclear about whether they improve your brain over all.
snippet: “Brain training” games have become big business, but the research is still unclear about whether they improve your brain over all.
lead_paragraph: “You just crashed a little bit,” Adam Gazzaley said.

abstract: The discovery will allow scientists to quickly, cheaply and easily test drugs that might stop the process in the first place.
snippet: The discovery will allow scientists to quickly, cheaply and easily test drugs that might stop the process in the first place.
lead_paragraph: For the first time, and to the astonishment of many of their colleagues, researchers created what they call Alzheimer’s in a Dish — a petri dish with human brain cells that develop the telltale structures of Alzheimer’s disease. In doing so, they resolved a longstanding problem of how to study Alzheimer’s and search for drugs to treat it; the best they had until now were mice that developed an imperfect form of the disease.

abstract: A number of conditions cause dementia-like symptoms, and doctors may have trouble diagnosing them. Still, the odds usually are low that an elderly family member can be made cognitively normal.
snippet: A number of conditions cause dementia-like symptoms, and doctors may have trouble diagnosing them. Still, the odds usually are low that an elderly family member can be made cognitively normal.
lead_paragraph: Maybe it’s something else.

abstract: Alzheimer’s occurs more often among older people who have used benzodiazepines for long periods, researchers report.
snippet: Alzheimer’s occurs more often among older people who have used benzodiazepines for long periods, researchers report.
lead_paragraph: I swear I don’t go looking for alarming news about benzodiazepines, drugs widely prescribed for insomnia and anxiety. But it shows up with some frequency, so, mindful of your fervidly held views on the subject, I am donning a hazmat suit to bring you the latest findings from the medical journal BMJ.

abstract: The artist, who has Alzheimer’s, is the subject of a film about his condition, and a production company alleges it was cut out of the project.
snippet: The artist, who has Alzheimer’s, is the subject of a film about his condition, and a production company alleges it was cut out of the project.
lead_paragraph: The country music singer and guitarist Glen Campbell is being sued by a Los Angeles-based media production group, the Record Company, which alleges that he reneged on an agreement to make the firm his partner in a documentary film about his struggle with Alzheimer’s. The suit was filed Monday in Superior Court in Los Angeles.

abstract: The state attorney general said Actavis’s plan to stop selling an older tablet in favor of a newer one was an attempt to maintain a monopoly.
snippet: The state attorney general said Actavis’s plan to stop selling an older tablet in favor of a newer one was an attempt to maintain a monopoly.
lead_paragraph: New York State’s attorney general filed an antitrust lawsuit on Monday seeking to stop a pharmaceutical company from forcing patients with Alzheimer’s disease to switch to a new version of a widely used drug. The lawsuit contends that the switch is designed to blunt competition from low-priced generic versions of the medication.

abstract: The factors that improve your chances of avoiding the Type 2 variety of the disease are unmistakable: weight loss and exercise.
snippet: The factors that improve your chances of avoiding the Type 2 variety of the disease are unmistakable: weight loss and exercise.
lead_paragraph: This year, nearly two million American adults and more than 5,000 children and adolescents will learn they have a potentially devastating, life-shortening, yet largely preventable disease: Type 2 diabetes. They will join 29.1 million Americans who already have diabetes.

headline.main: Beating Back the Risk of Diabetes
headline.print_headline: A Gradual Retreat From Diabetes

abstract: Even in patients with “pure” Alzheimer’s disease or another kind of dementia, most experts recommend greatly moderating alcohol consumption or eliminating it.
snippet: Even in patients with “pure” Alzheimer’s disease or another kind of dementia, most experts recommend greatly moderating alcohol consumption or eliminating it.
lead_paragraph: Q. Is there a difference between alcoholic dementia and “regular” dementia in the elderly?

abstract: A documentary airing on PBS provides a cleareyed account of one family’s struggle with Alzheimer’s disease.
snippet: A documentary airing on PBS provides a cleareyed account of one family’s struggle with Alzheimer’s disease.
lead_paragraph: When the documentary filmmaker Banker White began turning his camera on his family in 2009, his mother had undertaken a project of great personal importance: She wanted to compile material for a book about her own mother, a Massachusetts painter named Marian Williams Steele, who died of Alzheimer’s disease in 2001.

headline.main: A Picture of Dementia

abstract: Meryl Comer has written a heartbreaking account of caring for both her husband, who has been debilitated by early-onset Alzheimer’s disease, and her mother, who has the late-onset variety.
snippet: Meryl Comer has written a heartbreaking account of caring for both her husband, who has been debilitated by early-onset Alzheimer’s disease, and her mother, who has the late-onset variety.
lead_paragraph: I met Meryl Comer once, briefly, at a conference, and recall the juxtaposition of her sleek beauty and harrowing personal story: her husband, once chief of hematology and oncology at the National Institutes of Health, debilitated by early-onset Alzheimer’s disease, and her mother with the late-onset variety, both living in her suburban Maryland home, under her care.

snippet: Low vitamin D is associated with an increased risk for Alzheimer’s disease and other dementias, according to a new report.
lead_paragraph: Low vitamin D is associated with an increased risk for Alzheimer’s disease and other forms of dementia, according to a new report, though whether low vitamin D is a cause of the disorders remains unknown.

abstract: What I’d thought was depression was really was something else.
snippet: What I’d thought was depression was really was something else.
lead_paragraph: She lay so still as I approached her bed, I thought she was asleep. Or dead. Her eyes were open. “Mom?” I asked. Her gaze tilted toward me, but she said nothing.

headline.main: Her Own Kind of Absence

abstract: In this short documentary, the filmmaker Banker White explores how Alzheimer’s disease has revealed the strength of his parents’ marriage.

abstract: In this short documentary, a filmmaker explores how Alzheimer’s disease has revealed the strength of his parents’ marriage.
snippet: In this short documentary, a filmmaker explores how Alzheimer’s disease has revealed the strength of his parents’ marriage.
lead_paragraph: My mother, Pam White, has had a full life. In her 67 years, she has raised three happy children, enjoyed a rewarding career as a social worker and been a devoted partner to my father, Ed. But, as she puts it, “There’s just one little glitch.” In 2009, at age 61, she was told she had early-onset Alzheimer’s disease.

abstract: A home health aide cannot sue a couple with dementia for an injury sustained while caring for them, the California Supreme Court has ruled.
snippet: A home health aide cannot sue a couple with dementia for an injury sustained while caring for them, the California Supreme Court has ruled.
lead_paragraph: The California Supreme Court has ruled that a home health aide may not sue a client with Alzheimer’s disease for an injury incurred on the job. The case is one of the first in the nation to assess legal remedies available to paid caregivers who work with Alzheimer’s patients at home.

abstract: The one thing that brings him back from the confusion of Alzheimer’s is beauty — the yellow rose bush and the bleeding heart.
snippet: The one thing that brings him back from the confusion of Alzheimer’s is beauty — the yellow rose bush and the bleeding heart.
lead_paragraph: OMAHA — Mom is doing makeup for the opera and Dad tags along. Beverly Sills has been brought in for the role of Lucia di Lammermoor and she has packed the house. Mom draws wrinkles on a tenor while Ms. Sills is called to the stage. The page is growing urgent. She’ll miss her entrance if she doesn’t show up soon. A crew member blows by and says they found her in the green room, apparently smitten to the point of distraction by a big strapping cowboy, my father. Bill Rotert, Mom would scold, later, on their drive home.

abstract: While the drug, crenezumab, did not slow progression of the disease over all, at the highest doses it seemed to delay a decline in mental ability in patients with mild Alzheimer’s.
snippet: While the drug, crenezumab, did not slow progression of the disease over all, at the highest doses it seemed to delay a decline in mental ability in patients with mild Alzheimer’s.
lead_paragraph: Roche, the pharmaceutical company, on Wednesday reported mixed results in its latest trial of an Alzheimer’s drug. It said that while the drug did not slow progression of the disease over all, at the highest doses it did seem to delay a decline in mental ability in patients with mild cases of Alzheimer’s.

abstract: Exercise may help to keep the brain robust in people who have an increased risk of developing Alzheimer’s disease.
snippet: Exercise may help to keep the brain robust in people who have an increased risk of developing Alzheimer’s disease.
lead_paragraph: Exercise may help to keep the brain robust in people who have an increased risk of developing Alzheimer’s disease, according to an inspiring new study. The findings suggests that even moderate amounts of physical activity may help to slow the progression of one of the most dreaded diseases of aging.

abstract: Doctors in Ohio have developed a simple four-page quiz that can help reveal dementia early on, allowing patients to get their lives in order.

lead_paragraph: Liz Arledge is all too familiar with the ravages of dementia. Her mother died of Alzheimer’s, and one of her brothers has been found to have the progressive brain disease as well.

abstract: Intriguing research may point the way forward on treatment.
snippet: Intriguing research may point the way forward on treatment.
lead_paragraph: Two studies of Alzheimer’s disease published in respected scientific journals this month offered glimmers of hope for progress against this devastating neurological disorder. Neither advance is guaranteed to produce important clinical benefits anytime soon, but they may point the way toward new pathways to treat and diagnose a condition that impairs the thinking and memories of its victims and ultimately kills many of them.

abstract: Pat Bowlen, one of the N.F.L.’s longest-serving and most successful owners, relinquished control of the Denver Broncos, which was put in a trust as part of a plan that may lead to control by one of Bowlen’s children.
snippet: Pat Bowlen, one of the N.F.L.’s longest-serving and most successful owners, relinquished control of the Denver Broncos, which was put in a trust as part of a plan that may lead to control by one of Bowlen’s children.
lead_paragraph: Pat Bowlen, one of the N.F.L.’s longest-serving and most successful owners, relinquished control of the Denver Broncos because of his continuing battle with Alzheimer’s disease, the team said Wednesday.

abstract: Dementia is not something we doctors talk much about. We all have many patients with dementia — and more every year — but we never seem to chat about it the way we discuss kidney disease or cancer treatment.
snippet: Dementia is not something we doctors talk much about. We all have many patients with dementia — and more every year — but we never seem to chat about it the way we discuss kidney disease or cancer treatment.
lead_paragraph: “A fate worse than death,” my colleague muttered to me as we examined an elderly man admitted to the hospital with severe dementia.

headline.main: The Silence of Doctors Around Alzheimer’s

abstract: Watching over loved ones with dementia frequently presents new challenges, and a new book focuses on caregivers and the stressful situations they face.
snippet: Watching over loved ones with dementia frequently presents new challenges, and a new book focuses on caregivers and the stressful situations they face.
lead_paragraph: Paul Divinigracia does not consider himself a saint. But to observe how he cares for his wife, Virgie, now 11 years into Alzheimer’s disease, you might think otherwise.

headline.main: Caring for the Alzheimer’s Caregiver

abstract: Alzheimer’s, which has been linked to far more deaths than AIDS, has failed to garner the same national outrage and attention, even as AIDS deaths have begun to fall.
snippet: Alzheimer’s, which has been linked to far more deaths than AIDS, has failed to garner the same national outrage and attention, even as AIDS deaths have begun to fall.
lead_paragraph: The opening shots of “The Normal Heart,” HBO’s adaptation of Larry Kramer’s 1985 play about the early days of the AIDS crisis in New York, reveal a crew of sinewy and amorous young men disembarking from a ferry on Fire Island on a beautiful July day in 1981. The tableau is meant to suggest the final hour of unburdened desire, the moment before so much youth and beauty would be sacrificed to the cruelest attacks of physiology and cultural indifference.

abstract: A Georgia man who fatally shot an Alzheimer’s patient he feared was breaking into his house will not be charged with a crime, a prosecutor said.
snippet: A Georgia man who fatally shot an Alzheimer’s patient he feared was breaking into his house will not be charged with a crime, a prosecutor said.
lead_paragraph: ATLANTA — A man who shot to death an Alzheimer’s patient he feared was trying to break into his house will not be charged with a crime, a Georgia prosecutor said Friday.

abstract: The protein, which switches off at birth, reawakens in some older brains, protecting people from the memory and thinking problems of dementia, researchers say.
snippet: The protein, which switches off at birth, reawakens in some older brains, protecting people from the memory and thinking problems of dementia, researchers say.
lead_paragraph: It is one of the big scientific mysteries of Alzheimer’s disease: Why do some people whose brains accumulate the plaques and tangles so strongly associated with Alzheimer’s not develop the disease?

abstract: A writer says assisted suicide should be legal for the elderly even if they don’t face a terminal illness. Readers are invited to respond.

headline.main: Invitation to a Dialogue: Choosing When to Die
headline.print_headline: Invitation to a Dialogue: Choosing When to Die

abstract: The Friday before Father’s Day last year, my dad, an Alzheimer’s patient, wandered off from my mother at the grocery store. I’d been saying goodbye to him for almost a decade, but I wasn’t ready to lose him.
snippet: The Friday before Father’s Day last year, my dad, an Alzheimer’s patient, wandered off from my mother at the grocery store. I’d been saying goodbye to him for almost a decade, but I wasn’t ready to lose him.
lead_paragraph: While preparing my daughter for her preschool graduation ceremony last year, a text message buzzed my phone from my brother: “Dad has been missing for two hours.”

abstract: A couple, married for 28 years, considers an uncertain future because of the ravages of dementia.
snippet: A couple, married for 28 years, considers an uncertain future because of the ravages of dementia.
lead_paragraph: In December my wife and I moved out of our house into an independent-living apartment. Walking through the building, you might take it for a well-kept hotel, until you notice the handrails lining the hallways, the nursing assistants in the common areas and the people pushing walkers in front of them rather than pulling luggage carts behind them. The average resident is close to 80 years old.

abstract: After scientists found that blood from young mice rejuvenated the muscles and brains of old mice, experts said the research could lead to treatments for illnesses like Alzheimer’s disease.
snippet: After scientists found that blood from young mice rejuvenated the muscles and brains of old mice, experts said the research could lead to treatments for illnesses like Alzheimer’s disease.
lead_paragraph: Two teams of scientists published studies on Sunday showing that blood from young mice reverses aging in old mice, rejuvenating their muscles and brains. As ghoulish as the research may sound, experts said that it could lead to treatments for disorders like Alzheimer’s disease and heart disease.

abstract: She lived her last months in another family’s home.
snippet: She lived her last months in another family’s home.
lead_paragraph: WEST SHOKAN, N.Y. — IF my mother had been aware enough to know what we were spending on her care, she would have been aghast. She’d always been frugal. I once noticed the remains of the Easter ham in the refrigerator two months later. “Don’t you think it’s time to throw that out?” I asked. “Ham doesn’t go bad,” she explained. She could make a piece of tinfoil last clear into the next decade. She once made an old corduroy jumper of mine into a seat cover for the rocking chair — perfectly good material, not to be wasted.

abstract: A Georgia man who fatally shot an Alzheimer’s patient he feared was breaking into his house will not be charged with a crime, a prosecutor said.

abstract: Ben Affleck and Seth Rogen are set to testify before separate congressional committees Wednesday on separate subjects: Congo and Alzheimer’s disease.
snippet: Ben Affleck and Seth Rogen are set to testify before separate congressional committees Wednesday on separate subjects: Congo and Alzheimer’s disease.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Television and the movies cannot seem to resist juicy Washington settings — “House of Cards” (intrigue!), “Scandal” (high drama!) or maybe “Veep” (zany!) — but on Wednesday, Capitol Hill will provide the background for two Hollywood stars with real-life missions.

abstract: The National Institutes of Health, 10 drug companies and seven nonprofits will collaborate to speed the development of treatments for Alzheimer’s, Type 2 diabetes, rheumatoid arthritis and lupus.
snippet: The National Institutes of Health, 10 drug companies and seven nonprofits will collaborate to speed the development of treatments for Alzheimer’s, Type 2 diabetes, rheumatoid arthritis and lupus.
lead_paragraph: The National Institutes of Health, 10 large drug companies and seven nonprofit organizations announced  an unconventional partnership on Tuesday intended to speed up development of drugs to treat Alzheimer’s disease, Type 2 diabetes, rheumatoid arthritis and lupus.

headline.main: An Unusual Partnership to Tackle Stubborn Diseases
headline.print_headline: An Unusual Partnership to Tackle Stubborn Diseases

abstract: Otsuka said it would pay $17 a share in cash for Avanir, a California-based developer of treatments for Alzheimer’s, Parkinson’s and other neurological diseases.
snippet: Otsuka said it would pay $17 a share in cash for Avanir, a California-based developer of treatments for Alzheimer’s, Parkinson’s and other neurological diseases.
lead_paragraph: TOKYO — The Japanese pharmaceutical giant Otsuka Holdings said on Tuesday that it had struck a deal to buy Avanir Pharmaceuticals of California, a developer of treatments for Alzheimer’s, Parkinson’s and other neurological diseases, for $3.54 billion.

abstract: Dodging a scrum of reporters, former Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi of Italy on Friday began serving his sentence for tax fraud at a nursing home outside Milan.
snippet: Dodging a scrum of reporters, former Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi of Italy on Friday began serving his sentence for tax fraud at a nursing home outside Milan.
lead_paragraph: Dodging a scrum of reporters, former Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi of Italy on Friday began serving his sentence for tax fraud at a nursing home outside Milan. Mr. Berlusconi, 77, was ordered to serve a year of community service, and he will spend four hours a week assisting Alzheimer’s patients. He did not stop to speak with reporters, slipping in and out of the nursing home, which is in Cesano Boscone. On Thursday, he told a radio station that he was certain that he would be able to help “those in need” and that the experience would enrich him. He also said that he had been studying the latest treatments for Alzheimer’s.

abstract: The advanced case of C.T.E. in Bellini, a Brazilian who died in March, indicated again to researchers that the brain disease is not connected merely to boxers and American football players.
snippet: The advanced case of C.T.E. in Bellini, a Brazilian who died in March, indicated again to researchers that the brain disease is not connected merely to boxers and American football players.
lead_paragraph: Bellini, a Brazilian soccer star who led the team that won the 1958 World Cup and was honored with a statue outside the Estádio do Maracanã in Rio de Janeiro, had a degenerative brain disease linked to dozens of boxers and American football players when he died in March at age 83.

abstract: Tools like Lumosity promise to stimulate your mind, though researchers question how much they improve cognitive performance.
snippet: Tools like Lumosity promise to stimulate your mind, though researchers question how much they improve cognitive performance.
lead_paragraph: For a $14.95 monthly membership, the website Lumosity promises to “train” your brain with games designed to stave off mental decline. Users view a quick succession of bird images and numbers to test attention span, for instance, or match increasingly complex tile patterns to challenge memory.

abstract: Retired football players face a decision on whether to accept the proposed deal, to opt out and perhaps sue the league for more or to object and possibly appeal the settlement.
snippet: Retired football players face a decision on whether to accept the proposed deal, to opt out and perhaps sue the league for more or to object and possibly appeal the settlement.
lead_paragraph: Class-action settlements are often messy. When enough aggrieved people are thrown together, it is natural that some of them will be unhappy with a deal that is a result of a negotiation between parties trying to avoid a long, expensive trial with an uncertain outcome.

abstract: Dr. Joel S. Ross said he shared confidential information with Mathew Martoma on more than one occasion.
snippet: Dr. Joel S. Ross said he shared confidential information with Mathew Martoma on more than one occasion.
lead_paragraph: When Mathew Martoma, a hedge fund manager at SAC Capital Advisors, met Joel S. Ross, a prominent physician specializing in Alzheimer’s research, for dinner at a Midtown Manhattan restaurant, Mr. Martoma shocked Dr. Ross with a prescient question.

abstract: It’s associated with more happiness than you might think.

lead_paragraph: LAST week the biologist Richard Dawkins sparked controversy when, in response to a woman’s hypothetical question about whether to carry to term a child with Down syndrome, he wrote on Twitter: “Abort it and try again. It would be immoral to bring it into the world if you have the choice.”

abstract: A documentary presents a treatment for Alzheimer’s and other forms of dementia, while it offers profiles of people suffering from the disease.
snippet: A documentary presents a treatment for Alzheimer’s and other forms of dementia, while it offers profiles of people suffering from the disease.
lead_paragraph: The documentary “Do You Know What My Name Is?” introduces us to people with forms of dementia, like Alzheimer’s. It’s a condition that frightens many of us, because we’re worried that we’ll have it or will care for someone who has it, or because we’ve had experience with it. Films like “Away From Her” and the current release “Still Alice” meaningfully illustrate the challenges of the diagnosis.

abstract: We’re living longer than ever, but not always better.
snippet: We’re living longer than ever, but not always better.
lead_paragraph: The annual report on mortality rates by the National Center for Health Statistics, released this week, tells a now-familiar story: In 2012, life expectancy for older Americans continued to climb.

abstract: Jonatha Brooke talks about her mother’s descent into Alzheimer’s disease, the basis of her one-woman show, “My Mother Has 4 Noses.”
snippet: Jonatha Brooke talks about her mother’s descent into Alzheimer’s disease, the basis of her one-woman show, “My Mother Has 4 Noses.”
lead_paragraph: Outside, the sleet came down like needles, a perfect night for slipper socks and 1940s weepers on Turner Classic Movies. But no: I have tickets to “My Mother Has 4 Noses,” a one-woman musical written and performed by the singer/songwriter Jonatha Brooke about the harrowing years when she saw her mother through the final stages of Alzheimer’s disease.

abstract: Frequently a result of dementia, anosognosia is the inability to recognize one’s own impairment — a phenomenon caregivers know too well.
snippet: Frequently a result of dementia, anosognosia is the inability to recognize one’s own impairment — a phenomenon caregivers know too well.
lead_paragraph: Soon after his wife was diagnosed with frontotemporal dementia, Bill Floyd consulted a neurologist who had been a member of his church. People with this illness don’t know they have it, the doctor warned. They don’t understand that anything is wrong.

headline.main: When They Don’t Know They Are Ill

abstract: Why do we have to rest? Meet your brain’s janitorial staff.
snippet: Why do we have to rest? Meet your brain’s janitorial staff.
lead_paragraph: SLEEP seems like a perfectly fine waste of time. Why would our bodies evolve to spend close to one-third of our lives completely out of it, when we could instead be doing something useful or exciting? Something that would, as an added bonus, be less likely to get us killed back when we were sleeping on the savanna?

abstract: It was a long wait for those on a trapped research vessel, and if any of 338 sharks get too close to the Australian beach, they’ll send out tweets.
snippet: It was a long wait for those on a trapped research vessel, and if any of 338 sharks get too close to the Australian beach, they’ll send out tweets.
lead_paragraph: Nobody had a longer week than the 52 scientists, journalists and tourists waiting to be rescued from a vessel trapped in the frozen waters of East Antarctica. But for fishermen in Maine, where the shrimping season has been canceled because of a dearth of the crustaceans, it will be an even longer winter.

abstract: A British-American scientist and two Norwegians were awarded the prize for identifying the cells that help animals determine where they are.
snippet: A British-American scientist and two Norwegians were awarded the prize for identifying the cells that help animals determine where they are.
lead_paragraph: A British-American scientist and a pair of Norwegian researchers were awarded this year’s Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine on Monday for discovering “an inner GPS in the brain” that enables virtually all creatures to navigate their surroundings.

abstract: The trial of Mathew Martoma, a former SAC Capital Advisors portfolio manager, took a turn on Wednesday when Dr. Sidney Gilman, the government’s most important witness, showed signs of forgetfulness.
snippet: The trial of Mathew Martoma, a former SAC Capital Advisors portfolio manager, took a turn on Wednesday when Dr. Sidney Gilman, the government’s most important witness, showed signs of forgetfulness.
lead_paragraph: Dr. Sidney Gilman, the government’s most important witness in the insider trading trial of Mathew Martoma, a former SAC Capital Advisors portfolio manager, showed signs of a faulty memory on the stand on Wednesday.

abstract: Gurley acknowledged violating N.C.A.A. rules by accepting money for autographs, but those rules are under increased fire by critics who say athletes are being exploited. Georgia said it would appeal.
snippet: Gurley acknowledged violating N.C.A.A. rules by accepting money for autographs, but those rules are under increased fire by critics who say athletes are being exploited. Georgia said it would appeal.
lead_paragraph: Georgia running back Todd Gurley, who had been considered a top contender for the Heisman Trophy, must sit out until Nov. 15 for receiving more than $3,000 for signed memorabilia and other items over a two-year period, the N.C.A.A. announced Wednesday.

abstract: It’s not so much that the mental faculties of older people are rapidly declining, it’s that their databases are fuller, a new study suggests.
snippet: It’s not so much that the mental faculties of older people are rapidly declining, it’s that their databases are fuller, a new study suggests.
lead_paragraph: People of a certain age (and we know who we are) don’t spend much leisure time reviewing the research into cognitive performance and aging. The story is grim, for one thing: Memory’s speed and accuracy begin to slip around age 25 and keep on slipping.

abstract: In “Still Alice,” Julianne Moore plays a Columbia linguistics professor who receives a devastating diagnosis.
snippet: In “Still Alice,” Julianne Moore plays a Columbia linguistics professor who receives a devastating diagnosis.
lead_paragraph: “Still Alice” is a movie that addresses a nightmarish circumstance with calm, compassionate sensitivity. Based on Lisa Genova’s novel and directed by Richard Glatzer and Wash Westmoreland, it follows the deterioration of a Columbia linguistics professor who learns she has early-onset Alzheimer’s disease. Alice Howland (Julianne Moore), along with her husband and three children, must endure a cruel and absurd ordeal that has no real chance of growing easier. With what seems like shocking rapidity — the film’s chronology is appropriately fuzzy — Alice slides from a witty, intelligent, capable adult into a fragile and confused shadow of her former self.

lead_paragraph: Forest Laboratories said on Wednesday that it had agreed to buy Aptalis, a privately held drug maker, for $2.9 billion in cash.

abstract: The ceremony was at a yacht club in Wellfleet, Mass.
snippet: The ceremony was at a yacht club in Wellfleet, Mass.
lead_paragraph: Miriam Rebecca Marek, a daughter of Deborah Dwork and Dr. Kenneth L. Marek of New Haven, was married Saturday to Dr. Benjamin Alexander Kuritzkes, the son of Kit Chen Kuritzkes and Dr. Daniel R. Kuritzkes of Newton, Mass. Rabbi Amy E. Goodman officiated at the Chequesset Yacht and Country Club in Wellfleet, Mass.

abstract: A sense of purpose helps sustain people in old age, new studies show.
snippet: A sense of purpose helps sustain people in old age, new studies show.
lead_paragraph: My late father had a longtime friend, a retired kosher butcher, who lived down the hall in their South Jersey apartment building. Past 90, Manny was older and frailer than my father; he leaned on a cane and could barely see well enough to recognize faces. But every morning, and again in late afternoon, he walked through my dad’s unlocked front door to be sure he was all right and to kibitz a bit.

abstract: An associate of Steven A. Cohen said at the trial of Mathew Martoma, a former SAC Capital Advisors trader, that he was told of drug stock sales after the fact.
snippet: An associate of Steven A. Cohen said at the trial of Mathew Martoma, a former SAC Capital Advisors trader, that he was told of drug stock sales after the fact.
lead_paragraph: The billionaire investor Steven A. Cohen kept one of his closest associates at SAC Capital Advisors in the dark about the hedge fund’s rapid selling of a substantial stock position in two drug companies, just days before the companies reported disappointing results of a clinical trial for an Alzheimer’s drug.

headline.main: Colleague of SAC Leader Was Not Alerted to Trades
headline.print_headline: Colleague of SAC Leader Wasn’t Alerted to Trades

abstract: A court filing hints that several of Mathew Martoma’s co-workers at SAC Capital Advisors may be called as witnesses.
snippet: A court filing hints that several of Mathew Martoma’s co-workers at SAC Capital Advisors may be called as witnesses.
lead_paragraph: The criminal insider trading case against Mathew Martoma, the former SAC Capital Advisors portfolio manager, was built in part on interviews and depositions by federal authorities with several of his former colleagues at the hedge fund, according to a recent court filing.

abstract: Karlijn Keijzer, 25, and Quinn Schansman, 19, were on their way to vacations when the Malaysia Airlines jet was brought down.
snippet: Karlijn Keijzer, 25, and Quinn Schansman, 19, were on their way to vacations when the Malaysia Airlines jet was brought down.
lead_paragraph: To those who knew her at Indiana University, Karlijn Keijzer seemed to excel at everything she did, from her work as a doctoral student in chemistry to her leadership on the university’s rowing team.

abstract: Samsung Electronics will report its fourth-quarter earnings estimates, the insider trading trial of Mathew Martoma will begin and the European Central Bank will review its monetary policy.
snippet: Samsung Electronics will report its fourth-quarter earnings estimates, the insider trading trial of Mathew Martoma will begin and the European Central Bank will review its monetary policy.
lead_paragraph: SAMSUNG EARNINGS 2014 will be a tough year for Samsung Electronics, the largest cellphone and television maker in the world. Its stock recently took a beating amid concerns of slowing profit growth from smartphone sales, and the company is under pressure to continue releasing innovative new products to compete with Apple and a crop of handset makers in China. On Tuesday, when the South Korean giant is expected to report earnings estimates for the fourth quarter, investors will keep a close eye on the company’s sales of cellphones, televisions and other items during the holiday shopping season, the most lucrative time of year for electronics manufacturers.

abstract: At some point, you have to start indulging in the pleasures of the present.
snippet: At some point, you have to start indulging in the pleasures of the present.
lead_paragraph: THIS weekend, the singer and songwriter Leonard Cohen is celebrating his 80th birthday — with a cigarette. Last year he announced that he would resume smoking when he turned 80. “It’s the right age to recommence,” he explained.

abstract: The actress, who received two nominations, said she was stunned that a movie she shot in March was already up for awards.
snippet: The actress, who received two nominations, said she was stunned that a movie she shot in March was already up for awards.
lead_paragraph: The thing about living in New York and waiting for the big award nominations to be revealed is that they happen around 8:30 a.m. Eastern standard time, when most everyone in the city is already up. Which is what happened with Julianne Moore on Thursday. She was up, she had fed her kids and was trying to bide her time calmly until the Golden Globes nods came out.

abstract: The film, about a drummer and his abusive teacher, won the grand jury and audience awards.
snippet: The film, about a drummer and his abusive teacher, won the grand jury and audience awards.
lead_paragraph: It started Sundance with a bang and ended the festival with one: “Whiplash,” a drama about a drummer pushed to extremes by his deeply abusive teacher, won the top two prizes Saturday night in an off-kilter ceremony in Park City, Utah.
keywords: [{'name': 'subject', 'value': 'Sundance Film Festival (Park City, Utah)', 'rank': 1, 'major': 'N'}, {'name': 'persons', 'value': 'Chazelle, Damien', 'rank': 2, 'major': 'N'}, {'name': 'persons', 'value': 'Teller, Miles', 'rank': 3, 'major': 'N'}]
headline.main: ‘Whiplash’ Wins Sundance’s Top Prizes

abstract: Japanese scientists working with roundworms found that those with a genetic defect in a specific insulin receptor did not learn to avoid unpleasant situations the way other worms did.
snippet: Japanese scientists working with roundworms found that those with a genetic defect in a specific insulin receptor did not learn to avoid unpleasant situations the way other worms did.
lead_paragraph: Like Pavlov’s dogs, most organisms can learn to associate two events that usually occur together. Now, a team of researchers says they have identified a gene that enables such learning.

abstract: A floundering Brooklyn writer decamps to Florida to help his ailing parents and makes new friends and tighter family ties.
snippet: A floundering Brooklyn writer decamps to Florida to help his ailing parents and makes new friends and tighter family ties.
lead_paragraph: Though he’s played a committed writer on television (“October Road”), Bryan Greenberg doesn’t always come across as one in Michael Maren’s “A Short History of Decay.” That makes some sense, as Mr. Greenberg’s 30-something character, Nathan, just switched from being a struggling novelist to being an inactive playwright. But the best parts of Mr. Maren’s well-observed film aren’t always to be found in its accessible setup.

abstract: A small study shows that an antioxidant in chocolate appears to improve some memory skills that people lose as they age.
snippet: A small study shows that an antioxidant in chocolate appears to improve some memory skills that people lose as they age.
lead_paragraph: Science edged closer on Sunday to showing that an antioxidant in chocolate appears to improve some memory skills that people lose with age.

abstract: The new legislation is too limited.
snippet: The new legislation is too limited.
lead_paragraph: New York is finally joining the ranks of states that allow the use of marijuana for medical purposes, becoming the 23rd in the nation to do so. Too bad Governor Cuomo, who held the upper hand in bargaining because of his veto power, forced legislators to accept so many restrictions that the law will be a lot less useful than it could have been. The legislation has passed both chambers and is awaiting the governor’s signature.

abstract: Many people at risk of serious inherited diseases would like to know if they carry the genes, yet fear a positive result could be used against them.
snippet: Many people at risk of serious inherited diseases would like to know if they carry the genes, yet fear a positive result could be used against them.
lead_paragraph: About 700,000 Americans have had their DNA sequenced, in full or in part, and the number is rising rapidly as costs plummet — to $1,000 or less for a full genome, down from more than $1 million less than a decade ago.

abstract: We’ll never know what medical breakthroughs were missed because young scientists were not provided with resources.
snippet: We’ll never know what medical breakthroughs were missed because young scientists were not provided with resources.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — EVERY year the National Institutes of Health receives almost $30 billion in federal funds to invest in biomedical research. The bulk of that money goes to researchers who are in many cases esteemed in their fields — but also, in many cases, beyond the age when most scientists make their most important contributions to their fields.

abstract: Mathew Martoma sought to gain an “illegal edge” that helped him perpetrate the most lucrative insider trading scheme in history, a federal prosecutor said on Friday.
snippet: Mathew Martoma sought to gain an “illegal edge” that helped him perpetrate the most lucrative insider trading scheme in history, a federal prosecutor said on Friday.
lead_paragraph: Mathew Martoma, a former SAC Capital Advisors hedge fund manager, “corrupted” doctors to get an “illegal edge” that helped him perpetrate the most lucrative insider trading scheme in history, a federal prosecutor said on Friday.

abstract: Although patients often hear otherwise, Medicare does not require that they improve to keep receiving certain kinds of therapy.
snippet: Although patients often hear otherwise, Medicare does not require that they improve to keep receiving certain kinds of therapy.
lead_paragraph: Ever since Cindy Hasz opened her geriatric care management business in San Diego 13 years ago, she has been fighting a losing battle for clients unable to get Medicare coverage for physical therapy because they “plateaued” and were not getting better.

headline.main: A Quiet ‘Sea Change’ in Medicare

abstract: There is no rigorous scientific evidence that marijuana effectively treats the symptoms of many of the illnesses for which states have authorized its use.
snippet: There is no rigorous scientific evidence that marijuana effectively treats the symptoms of many of the illnesses for which states have authorized its use.
lead_paragraph: New York moved last week to join 22 states in legalizing medical marijuana for patients with a diverse array of debilitating ailments, encompassing epilepsy and cancer, Crohn’s disease and Parkinson’s. Yet there is no rigorous scientific evidence that marijuana effectively treats the symptoms of many of the illnesses for which states have authorized its use.

abstract: In a recent column, I mentioned that bridge club attendance has been hurt by the online sites.
snippet: In a recent column, I mentioned that bridge club attendance has been hurt by the online sites.
lead_paragraph: In a recent column, I mentioned that bridge club attendance has been hurt by the online sites. This is true even in the New York City area and New Jersey, which, according to the American Contract Bridge League, together had five of the top nine most successful clubs in North America in terms of tables in play last year.

abstract: Mr. Ned’s records and his sentimental style brought him a large following throughout Latin America.
snippet: Mr. Ned’s records and his sentimental style brought him a large following throughout Latin America.
lead_paragraph: Nelson Ned, a Brazilian singer of small stature and large voice who was hailed throughout Latin America as the “Little Giant of Song,” died on Sunday in São Paolo. He was 66.

abstract: Timothy Jandovitz, a former health care analyst, is scheduled to be the prosecution’s first witness at the insider trading trial of the former SAC manager Mathew Martoma.
snippet: Timothy Jandovitz, a former health care analyst, is scheduled to be the prosecution’s first witness at the insider trading trial of the former SAC manager Mathew Martoma.
lead_paragraph: When Timothy W. Jandovitz left SAC Capital Advisors after five years of grinding out financial numbers and analyzing companies, he decided to try his hand at pork belly and burrata-filled Belgian waffles.

headline.main: First Witness in Martoma Trial Took Detour to Waffle Business

abstract: An insurance underwriter, an employee of PricewaterhouseCoopers, an employment and labor lawyer and a New York bus driver are among the jurors chosen for the insider trading trial of Mathew Martoma, a former SAC Capital Advisors hedge fund manager.
snippet: An insurance underwriter, an employee of PricewaterhouseCoopers, an employment and labor lawyer and a New York bus driver are among the jurors chosen for the insider trading trial of Mathew Martoma, a former SAC Capital Advisors hedge fund manager...
lead_paragraph: A jury of seven women and five men was selected on Thursday to determine whether Mathew Martoma, a former SAC Capital Advisors hedge fund manager, is guilty of engaging in what the government has called the biggest insider trading scheme in history.

abstract: Mr. Agüeros went from a childhood in East Harlem to defending its Puerto Rican people as an antipoverty official as well as celebrating its culture by expanding and moving El Museo del Barrio.
snippet: Mr. Agüeros went from a childhood in East Harlem to defending its Puerto Rican people as an antipoverty official as well as celebrating its culture by expanding and moving El Museo del Barrio.
lead_paragraph: Jack Agüeros was an activist. The term is concise, like his many sonnets, but it hardly captures the expanse of his life, which saw him go from a childhood in East Harlem to defending its Puerto Rican people as an antipoverty official, celebrating its culture by expanding and moving El Museo del Barrio, and memorializing its greatest poet by translating the complete works of Julia de Burgos.

abstract: Mr. Suárez, who helped fill a power vacuum left by the death of Gen. Francisco Franco in 1975, was a key figure in the country’s transition back to democracy.
snippet: Mr. Suárez, who helped fill a power vacuum left by the death of Gen. Francisco Franco in 1975, was a key figure in the country’s transition back to democracy.
lead_paragraph: MADRID — Adolfo Suárez, Spain’s first elected prime minister after the Franco dictatorship and a key figure in the country’s transition back to democracy, died here on Sunday. He was 81.

lead_paragraph: FLYOVER LIVES: A Memoir,  by Diane Johnson. (Plume, $16.) The widely traveled author of the popular novel “Le Divorce,” among other books about Americans abroad, probes her Midwestern roots in this elegiac memoir. From the Friday night football of her youth in Illinois to the adventures illuminated in the letters and diaries of her stalwart pioneer ancestors, Johnson seeks to understand the people and geography that shaped her character.

lead_paragraph: COMANDANTE: Hugo Chávez’s Venezuela,  by Rory Carroll. (Penguin, $17.) Carroll spent six years covering Venezuela and Hugo Chávez (1954-2013) for The Guardian of London. He frames this sharp-eyed biography as a study of how the democratically elected strongman rose from poverty and prison to unrivaled influence as president, thumbing his nose at Washington while wielding his country’s oil reserves as a tool for Socialist-inspired change.

abstract: Paperback books of particular interest.

lead_paragraph: BELIEVING IS SEEING: Observations on the Mysteries of Photography,  by Errol Morris. (Penguin, $25.) Morris brings his great talent as a filmmaker to this investigation of the contested reality behind an eclectic range of documentary photographs — from the Crimean War, the Depression, Abu Ghraib and elsewhere. Intercutting his essays with maps, letters, timelines and interview excerpts, Morris “refines our most basic way of understanding the world,” Kathryn Schulz wrote here.

abstract: In a court filing, seven retired N.F.L. players say the current settlement does not adequately cover all retirees because only those with a limited number of illnesses will be eligible for cash awards.
snippet: In a court filing, seven retired N.F.L. players say the current settlement does not adequately cover all retirees because only those with a limited number of illnesses will be eligible for cash awards.
lead_paragraph: Seven retired N.F.L. players have asked an appeals court to intervene in the proposed settlement between the league and more than 4,500 retirees who say they were not told of the dangers of concussions and repeated head hits.

abstract: A day after the funeral for Avonte Oquendo, Senator Charles E. Schumer pushed for a new law that would finance a program to provide optional electronic tracking devices for children with autism.
snippet: A day after the funeral for Avonte Oquendo, Senator Charles E. Schumer pushed for a new law that would finance a program to provide optional electronic tracking devices for children with autism.
lead_paragraph: The day after the funeral of Avonte Oquendo, the boy with autism whose remains were found this month after he disappeared at age 14 from his school in October, his mother and grandmother stood with Senator Charles E. Schumer as he announced a proposal for a new law. Called “Avonte’s law,” it would finance a program to provide optional electronic tracking devices to be worn by children with autism.

abstract: Mr. Marshall, along with one of Brooke Astor’s former lawyers, was found guilty of criminal charges that they swindled millions from her after she was stricken with Alzheimer’s disease.
snippet: Mr. Marshall, along with one of Brooke Astor’s former lawyers, was found guilty of criminal charges that they swindled millions from her after she was stricken with Alzheimer’s disease.
lead_paragraph: Anthony D. Marshall, the only son of the philanthropist-socialite Brooke Astor, who with one of her former lawyers was found guilty of criminal charges that they swindled millions from his mother after she was stricken with Alzheimer’s disease, died on Sunday in Manhattan. He was 90.

abstract: The judge raised concerns that he might have to call in a fresh group of candidates on Thursday, postponing opening statements by a day.
snippet: The judge raised concerns that he might have to call in a fresh group of candidates on Thursday, postponing opening statements by a day.
lead_paragraph: After a full day of questioning dozens of potential candidates in a federal courtroom in Lower Manhattan on Wednesday, lawyers still had not selected the 12-member jury for the insider trading trial of Mathew Martoma, a former hedge fund manager at SAC Capital Advisors.

abstract: Jennifer Aniston, Jennifer Connelly and Reese Witherspoon are turning in low-glitter performances in films playing the festival.
snippet: Jennifer Aniston, Jennifer Connelly and Reese Witherspoon are turning in low-glitter performances in films playing the festival.
lead_paragraph: Updated, 5:15 p.m. | TORONTO — It takes a brave actress to rough herself up and appear on-screen without all the tricks and trade-craft that make beautiful people even more so in the movies.

abstract: Elan Pharmaceuticals is seeking to recoup the more than $1.5 million in legal fees it paid to comply with document requests by the federal government.
snippet: Elan Pharmaceuticals is seeking to recoup the more than $1.5 million in legal fees it paid to comply with document requests by the federal government.
lead_paragraph: Elan Pharmaceuticals is seeking to recoup the more than $1.5 million in legal fees it paid to comply with document requests by the federal government in its insider trading investigation of the hedge fund SAC Capital Advisors.

abstract: Francis criticized the administration that runs the Holy See for “ailments and temptations” like a narcissistic “pathology of power.”
snippet: Francis criticized the administration that runs the Holy See for “ailments and temptations” like a narcissistic “pathology of power.”
lead_paragraph: ROME — Pope Francis excoriated the Vatican bureaucracy in his traditional Christmas address on Monday, saying that some of the cardinals, bishops and priests who run the Roman Catholic Church suffer from a “spiritual Alzheimer’s.”

abstract: Assuming the judge approves it, the accord on the $760 million settlement could determine how retirees with head trauma are compensated.
snippet: Assuming the judge approves it, the accord on the $760 million settlement could determine how retirees with head trauma are compensated.
lead_paragraph: The N.F.L. and lawyers for the more than 4,000 former players who said the league hid from them the dangers of repeated hits to the head have agreed on the details of a $760 million settlement that could determine how retirees with head trauma are compensated.

snippet: Mr. Rebhorn appeared in dozens of popular movies and television shows and recently starred on the Showtime hit “Homeland.”
lead_paragraph: James Rebhorn, a character actor who appeared in dozens of popular movies and television shows and recently starred on the Showtime hit “Homeland,” died on Friday at his home in South Orange, N.J. He was 65.

headline.main: ‘Citizenfour’ Cements Favorite Status for Documentary Oscar

abstract: Peter Cott and Kenneth Leedom, interviewed in 2013, were a couple for almost 60 years, until Mr. Cott’s death on Nov. 14.
snippet: Peter Cott and Kenneth Leedom, interviewed in 2013, were a couple for almost 60 years, until Mr. Cott’s death on Nov. 14.
lead_paragraph: Peter Cott had just learned he had bladder cancer when he was interviewed last year for a Metropolitan cover article about his 58-year love affair with a man named Kenneth Leedom (“58 Years and Counting. A Love Story,” Sept. 8, 2013). The prognosis at the time was not bad, the couple said. They were newlyweds, declaratively in love, theatrical of bearing, refreshingly salty in their conversation. They were my mother’s neighbors.

abstract: Mr. Brown was a familiar presence at the murder trial of O.J. Simpson and became a public voice against domestic violence.
snippet: Mr. Brown was a familiar presence at the murder trial of O.J. Simpson and became a public voice against domestic violence.
lead_paragraph: Louis H. Brown Jr., the father of O. J. Simpson’s former wife, Nicole Brown Simpson, and a public voice against domestic violence, died on Thursday at his home in Dana Point, Calif., a seaside community in southern Orange County. He was 90.

abstract: This first novel probes the lives of three generations of an Irish-American family in the 20th century.
snippet: This first novel probes the lives of three generations of an Irish-American family in the 20th century.
lead_paragraph: As a young woman training for a graduate degree in nursing administration, Eileen Tumulty longs for the day when she will marry and take another name. It’s the thoroughgoing Irishness of Tumulty, with its redolence of “peat bogs and sloppy rebel songs” and deep defeat, from which she yearns to detach herself. She wants the sort of bland, decorous WASP name that will label her as an unhyphenated American. Bright, attractive and strong-willed, Eileen is passionately ambitious, determined to shake off the poverty-haunted, alcohol-ridden atmosphere of her childhood and achieve not only wealth and comfort but a sense of belonging. Shame is the deeply buried force that drives her.

abstract: Reading glasses should be a staple supply at facilities treating seniors, a psychiatrist suggests.
snippet: Reading glasses should be a staple supply at facilities treating seniors, a psychiatrist suggests.
lead_paragraph: The idea took shape as Dr. Shawn Barnes, a psychiatry resident at the University of California, San Diego, watched some hospitalized older patients struggling with consent forms.

abstract: The statements are the league’s most unvarnished admission yet that the sport’s professional participants sustain severe brain injuries at far higher rates than the general population.
snippet: The statements are the league’s most unvarnished admission yet that the sport’s professional participants sustain severe brain injuries at far higher rates than the general population.
lead_paragraph: The National Football League, which for years disputed evidence that its players had a high rate of severe brain damage, has stated in federal court documents that it expects nearly a third of retired players to develop long-term cognitive problems and that the conditions are likely to emerge at “notably younger ages” than in the general population.

abstract: With the conviction of Mr. Martoma, the nearly decade-long investigation of Steven Cohen and his hedge fund may have seen its last criminal prosecution.
snippet: With the conviction of Mr. Martoma, the nearly decade-long investigation of Steven Cohen and his hedge fund may have seen its last criminal prosecution.
lead_paragraph: Mathew Martoma had been on his way to being another American success story. Today, he is the eighth person who once worked for the hedge fund titan Steven A. Cohen to be convicted of insider trading.

abstract: Because the N.F.L.’s recent settlement promises payments to an unknown number of players, the $765 million called for in the deal could run out faster than expected.
snippet: Because the N.F.L.’s recent settlement promises payments to an unknown number of players, the $765 million called for in the deal could run out faster than expected.
lead_paragraph: As intriguing football matchups go, Sunday’s Super Bowl has nothing on one looming down the turnpike in federal court in Philadelphia — with Judge Anita B. Brody the ultimate referee.

abstract: Mr. Scott, who won the first and second Mr. Olympia competitions in the 1960s, also became Mr. America and Mr. Universe while influencing a generation of weight lifters.
snippet: Mr. Scott, who won the first and second Mr. Olympia competitions in the 1960s, also became Mr. America and Mr. Universe while influencing a generation of weight lifters.
lead_paragraph: Larry Scott, a renowned bodybuilder who won the first and second Mr. Olympia competitions in the 1960s and inspired a generation of musclemen, including a young upstart from Austria named Arnold Schwarzenegger, died on March 8 in Salt Lake City. He was 75.

abstract: His leadership in the early 1990s paved the way for a cease-fire with the Irish Republican Army and Loyalists, and ultimately to a peace accord.
snippet: His leadership in the early 1990s paved the way for a cease-fire with the Irish Republican Army and Loyalists, and ultimately to a peace accord.
lead_paragraph: DUBLIN — Albert Reynolds, the former Irish prime minister who played an important role in forging peace in Northern Ireland, died on Thursday at his home in Dublin. He was 81.

abstract: Lavish reproductions of work by Willem de Kooning, accompanied by research and historical anecdotes.
snippet: Lavish reproductions of work by Willem de Kooning, accompanied by research and historical anecdotes.
lead_paragraph: Mark Stevens and Annalyn Swan’s “De Kooning: An American Master,” which won a ­Pulitzer Prize in 2005, was billed as the first major biography of the artist. It covered most of the salient points: Willem de Kooning’s hardscrabble upbringing in Rotterdam; the sea voyage to America in 1926; his struggles with paint; his sexual affairs and the beloved child born out of wedlock (with a woman other than his wife of 45 years, Elaine de ­Kooning); the alcoholism that, remarkably, didn’t kill him. In his later years, de Kooning admitted he shouldn’t even be alive. After suffering from Alzheimer’s disease for more than a decade, he died in 1997 at the age of 92.

abstract: An appeals court acquitted the former Italian prime minister of paying for sex with a minor and revoked his seven-year sentence and ban from public office.
snippet: An appeals court acquitted the former Italian prime minister of paying for sex with a minor and revoked his seven-year sentence and ban from public office.
lead_paragraph: ROME — An appeals court in Milan on Friday overturned the conviction of the former Italian prime minister, Silvio Berlusconi, for paying for sex with a minor, and revoked his seven-year prison sentence and a lifetime ban from holding public office.

abstract: Television highlights.
snippet: Television highlights.
lead_paragraph: 2:45 P.M. (Starz) AMOUR (2012) An elderly French couple, portrayed by Jean-Louis Trintignant and Emmanuelle Riva, above, find their love tested when she has a stroke and he becomes her caretaker in this Oscar winner for best foreign-language film, directed by Michael Haneke. Isabelle Huppert plays their self-centered daughter — like her parents, a musician — whose questions about what she can do to help as her mother becomes increasingly incapacitated ring hollow. Manohla Dargis, writing in The New York Times, called this film “a masterpiece about life, death and everything in between.” And while some viewers may find the movie cold and even cruel, she added, “there’s another point to be made here, namely that all the violence in ‘Amour’ is crucial to Mr. Haneke’s rigorous, liberatingly unsentimental worldview, one that gazes on death with the same benevolent equanimity as life. All of which is to say: Bring hankies. This is a film that will make you weep not only because life ends but also because it blooms.”
headline.main: What’s On Wednesday
headline.print_headline: What’s On Wednesday

abstract: Television highlights.
snippet: Television highlights.
lead_paragraph: 10:30 P.M. (IFC) BOILER ROOM (2000) Before Martin Scorsese and Leonardo DiCaprio adapted the life of Jordan Belfort for the screen in “The Wolf of Wall Street,” Mr. Belfort inspired this fictional tale about a group of young, ruthless stockbrokers who work miles from the trading floor and use nothing but cold calls to relieve unsuspecting clients of their life savings. Giovanni Ribisi (above right, with Ben Affleck) plays Seth, a college dropout who joins the small firm of J. T. Marlin, rising quickly through its ranks, thanks to the no-nonsense tutelage of his possibly corrupt bosses and colleagues (portrayed by Mr. Affleck, Vin Diesel and Nicky Katt, among others). Writing in The New York Times, A. O. Scott said that the film, written and directed by Ben Younger, “reflects the sensibility of the generation it holds up to critical scrutiny, and it’s a cunningly ambiguous act of self-portraiture.” He added that Mr. Younger “presents a world ruled by a gang of lawless, soulless children, like the island of lost boys in ‘Peter Pan.’ But his film also shows us a group of actors, and a filmmaker, with soul to spare and talent to burn.”

abstract: Mr. Heilmeier in the 1960s helped invent a kind of screen display that used liquid crystals to project images — technology that is now ubiquitous in telephones, digital watches, computer monitors and flat-screen televisions.
snippet: Mr. Heilmeier in the 1960s helped invent a kind of screen display that used liquid crystals to project images — technology that is now ubiquitous in telephones, digital watches, computer monitors and flat-screen televisions.
lead_paragraph: George H. Heilmeier, an electrical engineer who in the 1960s helped invent a kind of screen display that used liquid crystals to project images — technology that is now ubiquitous in telephones, digital watches, computer monitors and flat-screen televisions — died April 21 in Plano, Tex. He was 77.

abstract: “The Radio Show,” a dance work by Kyle Abraham, honors a longtime Pittsburgh FM station and draws attention to disparities between youth and age.
snippet: “The Radio Show,” a dance work by Kyle Abraham, honors a longtime Pittsburgh FM station and draws attention to disparities between youth and age.
lead_paragraph: It helps that the seven dancers who were performing this weekend with Kyle Abraham/Abraham.In.Motion at the 92nd Street Y were all good-looking, well dressed, well lighted and very good movers. The work in which they appeared, Mr. Abraham’s “Radio Show,” featured deliberate ambiguities and tensions that, with other performers, could have easily turned it into a quite different piece. These dancers are so appealing that you’re on their side from the first.

abstract: A United States District Court judge heard hours of arguments about the fairness of the deal between the N.F.L. and its former players.
snippet: A United States District Court judge heard hours of arguments about the fairness of the deal between the N.F.L. and its former players.
lead_paragraph: PHILADELPHIA — After hundreds of court filings over the past 16 months, opponents of the preliminary settlement between the N.F.L. and the 5,000 former players who sued the league for hiding the dangers of concussions urged a federal judge on Wednesday to alter key parts of the deal.

abstract: Residents of the Prospect Park Residence say the plan, made known in a surprise announcement in March, did not provide for their needs and did not consider the lack of other housing options.
snippet: Residents of the Prospect Park Residence say the plan, made known in a surprise announcement in March, did not provide for their needs and did not consider the lack of other housing options.
lead_paragraph: A group of residents of the Prospect Park Residence, an assisted-living center for older people in Brooklyn that is scheduled to shut down in June, filed a lawsuit on Friday against it and the State Health Department, seeking to halt the closing.

abstract: Television highlights for Tuesday, March 25.
snippet: Television highlights for Tuesday, March 25.
lead_paragraph: 1:35 A.M. (Encore) SNATCH (2001) A diamond heist by a thief who also happens to be a gambling addict named Franky Four Fingers (Benicio Del Toro) sets off a chain of events in both the organized and the not-so-organized crime worlds of London, with two small-time boxing promoters (Jason Statham and Stephen Graham) and a Gypsy bare-knuckle boxer (Brad Pitt, above) caught in the middle. In his review in The New York Times, Elvis Mitchell said that the film’s writer and director, Guy Ritchie, “seizes the bespoke machismo of British gangster movies and gives it an action picture’s ferocity.” He added: “The effort is hyper-real, and he plays it for comic potential. Everything clicks into place by the end, though, in what is literally a shaggy dog story, with a cast of characters with florid names.”

abstract: For over 50 years Mr. Díaz was a presence in the cultural life of Venezuela and surrounding countries, “Uncle Simón” to fans of his cuatro music, radio and television shows and movies.
snippet: For over 50 years Mr. Díaz was a presence in the cultural life of Venezuela and surrounding countries, “Uncle Simón” to fans of his cuatro music, radio and television shows and movies.
lead_paragraph: Simón Díaz, one of Venezuela’s most popular singers and comedians who also earned recognition worldwide for his prowess as a player of the cuatro, a guitar-like instrument, died on Feb. 19 at his home in Caracas. He was 85.

abstract: Television highlights.
snippet: Television highlights.
lead_paragraph: 9 P.M. (HBO Signature) BEHIND THE CANDELABRA (2013) Michael Douglas, above, in a Golden Globe-winning role, stars as Liberace, and Matt Damon is Scott Thorson, his chauffeur, lover and adopted son, in this film from the director Steven Soderbergh and the screenwriter Richard LaGravenese. Set in Las Vegas; Los Angeles; and Palm Springs, Calif., the film chronicles the men’s relationship, as Liberace has Mr. Thorson cosmetically altered in his image and legally adopts him before discarding him for a younger model. “There’s something uncanny, even brilliant,” about Mr. Douglas’s impersonation of Liberace, Mike Hale wrote in The New York Times. “Sashaying across Las Vegas stages and epic suburban living rooms with a drum major’s puffed-up grandeur and a lounge lizard’s predatory smile, Mr. Douglas gives a performance so assured, so free of camp or cringe, that you quickly surrender any doubts you might have had about his playing a famously flamboyant, closeted-in-plain-sight gay entertainer.” Still, “a cerebral gloss on, and satire of, a big old Hollywood biopic,” Mr. Hale added, the film is “full of smart, funny details — perfectly sewn in place, like the rhinestones on one of Mr. Douglas’s blinding costumes — but it’s short on heart, or heat.”

abstract: Testimony by the chief counsel at SAC could allow prosecutors to scrutinize compliance at the multibillion-dollar hedge fund founded by Steven A. Cohen.
snippet: Testimony by the chief counsel at SAC could allow prosecutors to scrutinize compliance at the multibillion-dollar hedge fund founded by Steven A. Cohen.

abstract: Reaching out to Cuba while admonishing his own cardinals, Francis sends the right Christmas message.
snippet: Reaching out to Cuba while admonishing his own cardinals, Francis sends the right Christmas message.
lead_paragraph: There was a Christmas Eve a little more than a decade ago when I did something that was, for me, rare, at least on a holiday typically spent in full-party mode, with booze, food, family and friends. I went to church.

abstract: If a judge approves, Bart M. Schwartz, a former federal prosecutor who has served as an independent monitor in a number of government investigations, will be Steven A. Cohen’s minder.

headline.main: When Death Approaches Again

abstract: Slaughter in the Middle East cannot be an alibi for Israel to avoid self-scrutiny.
snippet: Slaughter in the Middle East cannot be an alibi for Israel to avoid self-scrutiny.
lead_paragraph: LONDON — Attending services at a Reform synagogue during the High Holy Days in London I heard sermons of great worthiness from British rabbis. One was about Alzheimer’s and dementia among the elderly and the need to honor the “fragment of the divine in everyone.” Another was about changes to the prayer book, including the dropping of the term “Lord,” with its male overtones.

abstract: In a court filing in Philadelphia, two doctors from the Brain Injury Association of America said the N.F.L.’s proposed settlement would exclude many players and limit their access to benefits.
snippet: In a court filing in Philadelphia, two doctors from the Brain Injury Association of America said the N.F.L.’s proposed settlement would exclude many players and limit their access to benefits.
lead_paragraph: A leading brain injury advocacy group said the proposed settlement between the N.F.L. and nearly 5,000 former players who sued the league for hiding from them the dangers of concussions is flawed because the definitions of eligibility are too narrow.

abstract: During Mr. Erburu’s 35 years at the company, Times Mirror acquired The Baltimore Sun, The Denver Post and the Long Island paper Newsday, as well as television stations, a book publisher and magazines.
snippet: During Mr. Erburu’s 35 years at the company, Times Mirror acquired The Baltimore Sun, The Denver Post and the Long Island paper Newsday, as well as television stations, a book publisher and magazines.
lead_paragraph: Robert F. Erburu, who as chief executive and chairman of the Times Mirror Company helped it become a diverse and powerful media enterprise that expanded well beyond its flagship property, The Los Angeles Times, before the paper and the company were sold, died on May 11 at his home in Santa Barbara, Calif. He was 83.

abstract: Our readers don’t want fourth-grade vocabulary or Dick-and-Jane syntax, but they need clear, digestible writing that doesn’t require three readings to understand. Here are a few sentences that tested their patience.
snippet: Our readers don’t want fourth-grade vocabulary or Dick-and-Jane syntax, but they need clear, digestible writing that doesn’t require three readings to understand. Here are a few sentences that tested their patience.
lead_paragraph: Our readers are often short of time, surrounded by distractions, and peering at small screens in supermarket checkout lines. No, they don’t want fourth-grade vocabulary or Dick-and-Jane syntax. But they need clear, digestible writing that doesn’t require three readings to understand.

abstract: The actress and author of “Let’s Just Say It Wasn’t Pretty” describes listening to Patti Smith’s audiobook of “Just Kids” as “a revelation.”
snippet: The actress and author of “Let’s Just Say It Wasn’t Pretty” describes listening to Patti Smith’s audiobook of “Just Kids” as “a revelation.”
lead_paragraph: The actress and author of “Let’s Just Say It Wasn’t Pretty” describes listening to Patti Smith’s audiobook of “Just Kids” as “a revelation” — “What is it about her voice? The way she uses her words and makes them sing?”

abstract: Mr. Böhm was typecast as heartthrob counts and princes until he starred in “Peeping Tom,” a controversial horror film. He later started an Ethiopian charity.
snippet: Mr. Böhm was typecast as heartthrob counts and princes until he starred in “Peeping Tom,” a controversial horror film. He later started an Ethiopian charity.
lead_paragraph: Karlheinz Böhm, an Austrian actor turned humanitarian whose early reputation rested on numerous portrayals of princely heartthrobs and one role as a serial killer who films the agonies of his female victims, died on May 29 in Grödig, Austria, near Salzburg. He was 86.

abstract: Ms. Guyse appeared on Broadway and in so-called race movies of the 1940s and ’50s. She also recorded an album of standards for MGM.
snippet: Ms. Guyse appeared on Broadway and in so-called race movies of the 1940s and ’50s. She also recorded an album of standards for MGM.
lead_paragraph: Sheila Guyse, a popular actress and singer who appeared on Broadway and in so-called race movies in the 1940s and ’50s, and who for a time, despite limited opportunities in the entertainment industry, appeared headed for broader fame, died on Dec. 28 in Honolulu. She was 88.

abstract: On the witness stand for a second day on Wednesday, Dr. Joel S. Ross told the jury that a former SAC Capital Advisors hedge fund manager, Mathew Martoma, knew the specific results of a clinical drug trial before they were publicly known.
snippet: On the witness stand for a second day on Wednesday, Dr. Joel S. Ross told the jury that a former SAC Capital Advisors hedge fund manager, Mathew Martoma, knew the specific results of a clinical drug trial before they were publicly known.
lead_paragraph: Prosecutors may not have any recorded conversations showing how a former SAC Capital Advisors trader, Mathew Martoma, engineered what they have called the biggest insider trading scheme in history. But testimony from one doctor indicates that Mr. Martoma knew the specific results of a clinical drug trial before they were known publicly.

abstract: He became the press spokesman for President Reagan after his boss, the press secretary James Brady, was wounded in an attempt on the life of the president.
snippet: He became the press spokesman for President Reagan after his boss, the press secretary James Brady, was wounded in an attempt on the life of the president.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Larry Speakes, who became the public face of Ronald Reagan’s presidency when a would-be assassin’s bullet gravely wounded his boss, press secretary James Brady, died Friday in his native Mississippi. He was 74.

abstract: Ms. Sizova’s talent was so great she went directly from school to soloist for the Kirov Ballet, often partnering with Rudolf Nureyev.
snippet: Ms. Sizova’s talent was so great she went directly from school to soloist for the Kirov Ballet, often partnering with Rudolf Nureyev.
lead_paragraph: Alla Sizova, one of the leading ballerinas of the Kirov Ballet during the 1960s and ’70s and an early partner of Rudolf Nureyev, died on Nov. 23 in St. Petersburg. She was 75.
